   "cell_type": "markdown",

   "source": [
    "## Influenza in Australia \n",
    "\n",
    "### Introduction \n",
    "\n",
    "_\"Gather insights from the provided dataset and develop a simple predictive model to forecast the volume of flu cases.\"_\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "__This notebook aims to benchmark vanilla models against a forecasting task.__ The data is influenza case counts in Australia over a period of roughly 9 years (data source:  http://www9.health.gov.au/cda/source/pub_influ.cfm). An introduction to the fields of the data will not be necessary as the solution's will have a sequential approach. The models to be benchmarked are:\n",
    "\n",
    "\t- Seasonal Random Walk\n",
    "\t- Seasonal Autoregressive Integrated Moving Average (SARIMA)\n",
    "\t- Recurrent Network\n",
    "    \n",
    "#### Table of Contents:\n",
    "\n",
    "\t1) Data Curation \n",
    "\t2) Sequence Building and Resampling\n",
    "\t3) Model Parameter Selection for SARIMA\n",
    "\t4) Parameter Testing for SARIMA\n",
    "\t5) Sequence Building for RNN\n",
    "\t6) LSTM Model   \n",
    "    7) Final Metrics\n",
    "    \n",
    "## 1) Data Curation \n",
    "\n",
    "Importing necessary packages for python and setting visualisation backends."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 88,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import pandas as pd\n",
    "import statsmodels.api as sm  \n",
    "import datetime \n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "import matplotlib.dates as mdates\n",
    "import seaborn as sns\n",
    "from statsmodels.tsa.stattools import adfuller\n",
    "from statsmodels.graphics.tsaplots import plot_acf\n",
    "from statsmodels.tsa.seasonal import seasonal_decompose\n",
    "from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error\n",
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "from math import sqrt\n",
    "\n",
    "%matplotlib inline\n",
    "sns.set()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Importing data. It is useful to point out that the original data was in XML format. I got rid of the formatting in Microsoft Excel and exported the raw data to a CSV format to ease the process in Pandas.\n",
    "\n",
    "Next, the naming and typing conventions are dealt with. Turning the features to strings and dates to np.datetime64 objects. In addition to these conventions, a single field is created encoding the year the record was recorded. Although could be parsed later from the datetime object, I do this for convenience as the dataset is small with no memory problems.   "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 89,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# import\n",
    "influenza = pd.read_csv('influenza.csv')\n",
    "\n",
    "# consistent naming convention\n",
    "influenza.columns = ['week', 'state', 'age', 'sex', 'indigenous', 'type'] \n",
    "\n",
    "# typing \n",
    "influenza.week = pd.to_datetime(influenza.week)\n",
    "influenza.state = influenza.state.astype('str')\n",
    "influenza.age = influenza.age.astype('str')\n",
    "influenza.sex = influenza.sex.astype('str')\n",
    "influenza.indigenous = influenza.indigenous.astype('str')\n",
    "influenza.type = influenza.type.astype('str')\n",
    "\n",
    "# adding year column\n",
    "influenza['year'] = [i.year for i in influenza.week]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "During my exploration of the data in Tableau, I see that there are vast differences in collected data over the years. This _could_ be due to the number of cases (maybe people just got really sick that year..), however, this could also be a data quality issue. This is a risk not worth taking. It is useful to look at the gaps in the data.  "
   ]
  },
  {

    "plt.figure(figsize=(20,8))\n",
    "influenza.groupby('year').count()['week'].plot.pie(autopct=\"%.1f%%\")\n",
    "plt.title(\"yearly number of cases\", fontsize=14)\n",
    "plt.ylabel(\"\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The majority (86.2 %) of the cases recorded is from 2010-2017 and we have some missing data points, the absence of the data points _could_ be due to zero cases recorded at the time for the territories however I will still take action on them.  \n",
    "\n",
    "#### Actions:\n",
    "\n",
    "- not taking 2018 - incomplete data for 2018 (keeping it clean, not using it, it is just one wk of data)\n",
    "- not taking 2009 - in order to not introduce drift for, H1N1 pandemic of 2009 (the spike you see at 8.5% in 2009)\n",
    "- not taking 2008 - 2009 not being in the modeling, going to not use 2008 as well. Do not want to patch for a year\n",
    "- Prior to 2014, there seems to be missing data for some states compared to after 2014.. will need to patch\n",
    "\n",
    "now will need to do some patching of the missing sequences in some states."
   ]
  },

      "51 weeks are missing in Vic - 2018\n",
      "51 weeks are missing in WA - 2018\n",
      "51 weeks are missing in Tas - 2018\n",
      "4 weeks are missing in Tas - 2015\n",
      "13 weeks are missing in Tas - 2013\n",
      "5 weeks are missing in NT - 2012\n",
      "7 weeks are missing in Tas - 2012\n",
      "4 weeks are missing in NT - 2011\n",
      "8 weeks are missing in Tas - 2011\n",
      "15 weeks are missing in NT - 2010\n",
      "17 weeks are missing in Tas - 2010\n",
      "9 weeks are missing in NT - 2009\n",
      "6 weeks are missing in SA - 2009\n",
      "3 weeks are missing in Vic - 2009\n",
      "21 weeks are missing in Tas - 2009\n",
      "12 weeks are missing in NT - 2008\n",
      "20 weeks are missing in SA - 2008\n",
      "17 weeks are missing in Tas - 2008\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# as we are dealing with sequential data, it is important to chech for data quality. \n",
    "# is the sequence consistent for each year & each state? \n",
    "\n",
    "for year in influenza.year.unique():\n",
    "    for state in influenza.state.unique():\n",
    "        recorded_wks = len(influenza[(influenza.year == year) & (influenza.state == state)].week.unique())\n",
    "        if recorded_wks < 50:\n",
    "            print (\"{} weeks are missing in {} - {}\".format(52 - recorded_wks, state , year)) "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 92,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "NSW has 418 records between 2010 & 2017\n",
      "NT has 387 records between 2010 & 2017\n",
      "QLD has 418 records between 2010 & 2017\n",
      "SA has 416 records between 2010 & 2017\n",
      "TAS has 367 records between 2010 & 2017\n",
      "VIC has 418 records between 2010 & 2017\n",
      "WA has 417 records between 2010 & 2017\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# taking the subset we will be dealing with\n",
    "\n",
    "influenza_subset = influenza[influenza.year.isin(['2010', '2011', '2012', '2013', '2014', '2015', '2016', '2017'])]\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "NSW = influenza_subset[influenza_subset.state == 'NSW'].reset_index(drop='index')\n",
    "NT = influenza_subset[influenza_subset.state == 'NT'].reset_index(drop='index')\n",
    "QLD = influenza_subset[influenza_subset.state == 'Qld'].reset_index(drop='index')\n",
    "SA = influenza_subset[influenza_subset.state == 'SA'].reset_index(drop='index')\n",
    "TAS = influenza_subset[influenza_subset.state == 'Tas'].reset_index(drop='index')\n",
    "VIC = influenza_subset[influenza_subset.state == 'Vic'].reset_index(drop='index')\n",
    "WA = influenza_subset[influenza_subset.state == 'WA'].reset_index(drop='index')\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "# checking how many weeks each state has generated reports\n",
    "\n",
    "print('NSW has {} records between 2010 & 2017'.format(len(NSW.sort_values('week').week.unique())))\n",
    "print('NT has {} records between 2010 & 2017'.format(len(NT.sort_values('week').week.unique())))\n",
    "print('QLD has {} records between 2010 & 2017'.format(len(QLD.sort_values('week').week.unique())))\n",
    "print('SA has {} records between 2010 & 2017'.format(len(SA.sort_values('week').week.unique())))\n",
    "print('TAS has {} records between 2010 & 2017'.format(len(TAS.sort_values('week').week.unique())))\n",
    "print('VIC has {} records between 2010 & 2017'.format(len(VIC.sort_values('week').week.unique())))\n",
    "print('WA has {} records between 2010 & 2017'.format(len(WA.sort_values('week').week.unique())))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 2) Sequence Building and Resampling\n",
    "\n",
    "NSW, QLD, & VIC generated the most & the same number of reports between 2010 & 2017. Before taking their timestamps as a skeleton for our time-series, we should check if these states' timelines are aligned."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 93,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "All timestamps are in alignment\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "match_set = [set(NSW.sort_values('week').week.unique() == state.sort_values('week').week.unique()) for state in [QLD,VIC]]\n",
    "if match_set == [{True}, {True}]:\n",
    "    print('All timestamps are in alignment')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "As the timestamps are in alignment we can go ahead and take the timestamps as a basis to build our series. For this, we create a mapping just to keep everything in order. \n",
    "\n",
    "- 0 -> date 1\n",
    "- 1 -> date 2\n",
    "- 2 -> date 3 ..."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 94,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# taking NSW timestamps as base for sequence and building a dictionary for it: \n",
    "\n",
    "sequence = dict(zip(pd.to_datetime(NSW.sort_values('week').week.unique()), range(len(NSW.sort_values('week').week.unique()))))\n",
    "\n",
    "# inverse mapping - maybe useful\n",
    "\n",
    "inv_map_sequence = {v: k for k, v in sequence.items()}"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Now we have clear definitions of our sequences. \n",
    "\n",
    "#### Action:\n",
    "\n",
    "- Finding missing sequences in each state and patch them with linear interpolation"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 95,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# adding sequence column to dataframes - to replace timestamps:\n",
    "\n",
    "NSW['sequence'] = [sequence[i] for i in NSW.week]\n",
    "NT['sequence'] = [sequence[i] for i in NT.week]\n",
    "QLD['sequence'] = [sequence[i] for i in QLD.week]\n",
    "SA['sequence'] = [sequence[i] for i in SA.week]\n",
    "TAS['sequence'] = [sequence[i] for i in TAS.week]\n",
    "VIC['sequence'] = [sequence[i] for i in VIC.week]\n",
    "WA['sequence'] = [sequence[i] for i in WA.week]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 96,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# overwriting state dataframes with time-series of counts of events grouped by their sequences\n",
    "\n",
    "NSW = NSW.groupby('sequence').count()['state'].reset_index()\n",
    "NT = NT.groupby('sequence').count()['state'].reset_index()\n",
    "QLD = QLD.groupby('sequence').count()['state'].reset_index()\n",
    "SA = SA.groupby('sequence').count()['state'].reset_index()\n",
    "TAS = TAS.groupby('sequence').count()['state'].reset_index()\n",
    "VIC = VIC.groupby('sequence').count()['state'].reset_index()\n",
    "WA = WA.groupby('sequence').count()['state'].reset_index()\n",
    "\n",
    "NSW.columns = ['sequence', 'nsw_case_count']\n",
    "NT.columns = ['sequence', 'nt_case_count']\n",
    "QLD.columns = ['sequence', 'qld_case_count']\n",
    "SA.columns = ['sequence', 'sa_case_count']\n",
    "TAS.columns = ['sequence', 'tas_case_count']\n",
    "VIC.columns = ['sequence', 'vic_case_count']\n",
    "WA.columns = ['sequence', 'wa_case_count']\n",
    "\n",
    "NSW['date'] = [inv_map_sequence[i] for i in NSW.sequence]\n",
    "NT['date'] = [inv_map_sequence[i] for i in NT.sequence]\n",
    "QLD['date'] = [inv_map_sequence[i] for i in QLD.sequence]\n",
    "SA['date'] = [inv_map_sequence[i] for i in SA.sequence]\n",
    "TAS['date'] = [inv_map_sequence[i] for i in TAS.sequence]\n",
    "VIC['date'] = [inv_map_sequence[i] for i in VIC.sequence]\n",
    "WA['date'] = [inv_map_sequence[i] for i in WA.sequence]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 97,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# as we took NSW - QLD & VIC's time line for skeleton, \n",
    "# we concat their sequence columns to the rest to see the gaps in other states. Taking NSW\n",
    "\n",
    "# NSW stays the same\n",
    "# NT \n",
    "NT = pd.merge(NSW, NT, on='sequence', how='outer').drop(['nsw_case_count', 'date_y'], axis=1)\n",
    "NT.columns = ['sequence', 'date', 'case_count']\n",
    "# QLD (don't really need to do it, as has same sequence count already as NSW but doing it anyway - paranoid :D)\n",
    "QLD = pd.merge(NSW, QLD, on='sequence', how='outer').drop(['nsw_case_count', 'date_y'], axis=1)\n",
    "QLD.columns = ['sequence', 'date', 'case_count']\n",
    "# SA \n",
    "SA = pd.merge(NSW, SA, on='sequence', how='outer').drop(['nsw_case_count', 'date_y'], axis=1)\n",
    "SA.columns = ['sequence', 'date', 'case_count']\n",
    "# TAS\n",
    "TAS = pd.merge(NSW, TAS, on='sequence', how='outer').drop(['nsw_case_count', 'date_y'], axis=1)\n",
    "TAS.columns = ['sequence', 'date', 'case_count']\n",
    "# VIC (don't need to do it but doing it anyway .. )\n",
    "VIC = pd.merge(NSW, VIC, on='sequence', how='outer').drop(['nsw_case_count', 'date_y'], axis=1)\n",
    "VIC.columns = ['sequence', 'date', 'case_count']\n",
    "# WA\n",
    "WA = pd.merge(NSW, WA, on='sequence', how='outer').drop(['nsw_case_count', 'date_y'], axis=1)\n",
    "WA.columns = ['sequence', 'date', 'case_count']\n",
    "# change NSW column names for consistent naming\n",
    "NSW.columns = ['sequence', 'case_count', 'date']\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 98,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# now we have set up everything for a clear linear interpolation \n",
    "# vanilla interpolate does it in a linear fashion. It is an 'in-between' method. So edges wouldn't be filled\n",
    "# TAS has edge values missing (ex: the very first part of the sequence 0, this can't be filled in like that)\n",
    "# for this reason we can use .bfill().ffill() methods sequentially in order to fill in the nearest value \n",
    "# for these edge cases\n",
    "\n",
    "NSW = NSW.interpolate().bfill().ffill()\n",
    "NT = NT.interpolate().bfill().ffill()\n",
    "QLD = QLD.interpolate().bfill().ffill()\n",
    "SA = SA.interpolate().bfill().ffill()\n",
    "TAS = TAS.interpolate().bfill().ffill()\n",
    "VIC = VIC.interpolate().bfill().ffill()\n",
    "WA = WA.interpolate().bfill().ffill()\n",
    "\n",
    "# turn case counts back to int type after interpolation\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "NSW.case_count = NSW.case_count.astype(int)\n",
    "NT.case_count = NT.case_count.astype(int)\n",
    "QLD.case_count = QLD.case_count.astype(int)\n",
    "SA.case_count = SA.case_count.astype(int)\n",
    "TAS.case_count = TAS.case_count.astype(int)\n",
    "VIC.case_count = VIC.case_count.astype(int)\n",
    "WA.case_count = WA.case_count.astype(int)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "##### Time-Series plots for each state"

    "sns.lineplot(data=WA, x=\"sequence\", y=\"case_count\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "There seems to be the same seasonality for each state. So we can add the signals together. This also makes things more simple. We combine the signals to create a complete **national influenza time-series** \n",
    "\n",
    "To create further consistency in the signal and since the task asks to forecast '6 months ahead', I resample the time series in an additive fashion to end up with a monthly time-series.  There are some technical semantics with building this in Pandas, the below cell takes care of the series."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 107,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "%%capture\n",
    "AU = pd.concat([NSW, QLD, VIC, SA, NT, TAS, WA]).groupby('date').sum()\n",
    "AU_seq = AU.reset_index()\n",
    "AU_date = AU.index\n",
    "AU_case = AU.case_count\n",
    "AU = pd.Series(data = AU_case, index = AU_date)\n",
    "AU.sort_index(inplace=True)\n",
    "# getting dates for closest sunday so series object can have a frequency attribute\n",
    "# first resampling it by week to get alignment on dates - cheking if we can.\n",
    "AU_influenza = AU.resample(\"W\").sum()\n",
    "##################################################################################\n",
    "# final Australia dataframe with Weekly-frq\n",
    "date = AU_influenza.index\n",
    "AU_influenza = pd.Series(data = list(AU_case), index = date)\n",
    "# monthly resample to complete the job.\n",
    "AU_influenza = AU_influenza.resample(\"M\").sum()"
   ]
  },

   "source": [
    "## 3) Model Parameter Selection for SARIMA\n",
    "\n",
    "Although clearly see the trend rise over time we would still want to test stationariness with the Dickey-Fuller test.\n",
    "\n",
    "Ho = 'Time Series is Non-Stationary'"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 110,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def test_stationary(df): \n",
    "    print('DF Statistic: {}'.format(adfuller(df)[0]))\n",
    "    print('DF crit value: {}'.format(adfuller(df)[4]['1%']))\n",
    "    print('DF crit value: {}'.format(adfuller(df)[4]['5%']))\n",
    "    print('DF crit value: {}'.format(adfuller(df)[4]['10%']))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 111,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "DF Statistic: 1.486989613442251\n",
      "DF crit value: -3.510711795769895\n",
      "DF crit value: -2.8966159448223734\n",
      "DF crit value: -2.5854823866213152\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "test_stationary(AU_influenza)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Although the DF value is much larger then the 5% crit value, cannot reject the null hypothesis. We try to make the series stationary for an autocorrelation plot.  "

    "- Autocorrelations have good number of positives in high lag and has a pattern so may need differencing. However, as mentioned, influenza 'trends' seem to rise one year and fall for the next few. It would be very bold to add and Integrated value into an ARIMA for a long term forecast for a signal like this. So will keep differencing at a zero.  \n",

   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 4) Parameter Testing for SARIMA\n",
    "\n",
    "We split the series into train and test. We then fit the ARIMA with the parameter ranges we chose. Benchmark them against a MSE for the test series "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 119,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "split = round((len(AU_influenza) * 70) / 100)\n",
    "train = AU_influenza[0:split]\n",
    "test = AU_influenza[split:]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 120,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "%%capture\n",
    "combo = []\n",
    "mse = []\n",
    "for p in (1,3):\n",
    "    for q in (1,3):\n",
    "            \n",
    "        mod = sm.tsa.statespace.SARIMAX(train, trend='n', seasonal_order=(p,0,q,12), initialization='approximate_diffuse', enforce_stationarity=False)\n",
    "        results = mod.fit()\n",
    "        forecast = results.predict(start = split, end= len(AU_influenza) -1 , dynamic= True)  \n",
    "        m = mean_squared_error(test, forecast)\n",
    "        combo.append((p,0,q))\n",
    "        mse.append(sqrt(m))\n",
    "            \n",
    "results = pd.DataFrame(data=[combo,mse]).T\n",
    "results.columns = ['arima', 'mse']"
   ]
  },

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "As we prooved that the series was not stable, we should do a SARIMA with the stable series. We prooved that only differencing the series with one-step stablized the series. So we can define two functions:\n",
    "\n",
    "- one to difference the series\n",
    "- one to invert the difference"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 124,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# create a differenced series\n",
    "def difference(dataset, interval=1):\n",
    "    diff = list()\n",
    "    for i in range(interval, len(dataset)):\n",
    "        value = dataset[i] - dataset[i - interval]\n",
    "        diff.append(value)\n",
    "    return pd.Series(diff)\n",
    " \n",
    "# invert differenced value\n",
    "def inverse_difference(history, yhat, interval=1):\n",
    "    return yhat + history[-interval]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 125,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "stable_AU_influenza = difference(AU_influenza)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 126,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "[<matplotlib.lines.Line2D at 0x7ff1491dcbd0>]"

     "output_type": "execute_result"

   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 47,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stderr",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "/opt/anaconda/lib/python3.7/site-packages/ipykernel_launcher.py:5: FutureWarning: The signature of `Series.to_csv` was aligned to that of `DataFrame.to_csv`, and argument 'header' will change its default value from False to True: please pass an explicit value to suppress this warning.\n",
      "  \"\"\"\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# Getting a random walk for benchmark \n",
    "mod = sm.tsa.statespace.SARIMAX(AU_influenza, trend='n', order=(0,0,0), seasonal_order=(0,1,0,12),initialization='approximate_diffuse', enforce_stationarity=False)\n",
    "results = mod.fit()\n",
    "rw_forecast = results.predict(start = len(AU_influenza), end= len(AU_influenza) + 6 , dynamic= True)  \n",
    "rw_forecast.to_csv('rw_forecast.csv')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 5) Sequence Building for RNN"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 94,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# imports \n",
    "\n",
    "# for scaling - transforming arrays\n",
    "from sklearn.preprocessing import MinMaxScaler\n",
    "# mse function for error evaluation\n",
    "from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error\n",
    "# model building framework\n",
    "from keras.models import Sequential\n",
    "# dense mlp layer for trainable weights - linear\n",
    "from keras.layers import Dense\n",
    "# lstm cell layer\n",
    "from keras.layers import LSTM\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "# create a differenced series\n",
    "def difference(dataset, interval=1):\n",
    "    diff = list()\n",
    "    for i in range(interval, len(dataset)):\n",
    "        value = dataset[i] - dataset[i - interval]\n",
    "        diff.append(value)\n",
    "    return pd.Series(diff)\n",
    " \n",
    "# invert differenced value\n",
    "def inverse_difference(history, yhat, interval=1):\n",
    "    return yhat + history[-interval]\n",
    "\n",
    "# invert the scaling done by minmaxscaler\n",
    "def invert_scale(scaler, X, value):\n",
    "    new_row = [x for x in X] + [value]\n",
    "    array = numpy.array(new_row)\n",
    "    array = array.reshape(1, len(array))\n",
    "    inverted = scaler.inverse_transform(array)\n",
    "    return inverted[0, -1]\n",
    "\n",
    "# step by step forecasting\n",
    "def forecast_lstm(model, batch_size, X):\n",
    "    X = X.reshape(1, 1, 1)\n",
    "    yhat = model.predict(X, batch_size=batch_size)\n",
    "    return yhat[0,0]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "- Stablize the time-series\n",
    "- This is a supervised problem, we need lables, which are one time step ahead of the training points in sequence\n",
    "- Create the sets and split them to training testing\n",
    "- Fit transformer to the training set and scale both training and testing set with the transformer"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 95,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "split = round((len(AU_influenza) * 70) / 100)\n",
    "train = AU_influenza[0:split]\n",
    "test = AU_influenza[split:]\n",
    "\n",
    "# get stationary values\n",
    "\n",
    "AU_influenza_ = difference(pd.DataFrame(AU_influenza).reset_index().drop('date', axis=1).values)\n",
    "\n",
    "# we need a supervised approach for LSTM networks (where x is step t-1 and y is step t). Building that data frame below\n",
    "x = pd.DataFrame(AU_influenza_).shift(1).fillna(0).values\n",
    "y = pd.DataFrame(AU_influenza_).values\n",
    "\n",
    "# apply split \n",
    "x_train = x[:split]\n",
    "y_train = y[:split]\n",
    "x_test = x[split:]\n",
    "y_test = y[split:]\n",
    "\n",
    "# transform arrays based on training data, transform training and testing data\n",
    "transform = MinMaxScaler(feature_range=(-1,1)).fit(x_train)\n",
    "x_train = transform.transform(x_train)\n",
    "y_train = transform.transform(y_train)\n",
    "x_test = transform.transform(x_test)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 96,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# reshape tensor\n",
    "\n",
    "x_train = x_train.reshape(x_train.shape[0], 1, x_train.shape[1])"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## 6) LSTM Model\n",
    "\n",
    "cannot test a lot of parameters due to computation. resetting states to not have it cleared (which is what happens by default between batches). This control is obtained by adding the 'stateful' flag in the LSTM layer.\n",
    "\n",
    "- 5 Neurons in LSTM layer\n",
    "- Using 1 neuron in the dense layer to get output right after LSTM - as we do not have much data to train, want to keep parameters to a low\n",
    "- Stateful\n",
    "- 2000 epochs"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 97,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "model = Sequential()\n",
    "model.add(LSTM(5, batch_input_shape=(1, x_train.shape[1], x_train.shape[2]), stateful=True))\n",
    "model.add(Dense(1))\n",
    "model.compile(loss='mean_squared_error', optimizer='adam')\n",
    "for i in range(2000):\n",
    "    model.fit(x_train, y_train, epochs=1, batch_size=1, verbose=0, shuffle=False)\n",
    "    model.reset_states()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Predict the entire training set to get the cell states for validation"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 98,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "%%capture\n",
    "train_reshaped = x_train.reshape(len(x_train), 1, 1)\n",
    "model.predict(train_reshaped, batch_size=1)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 99,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "predictions = list()\n",
    "for i in range(len(x_test)):\n",
    "    yhat = forecast_lstm(model, 1, x_test[i])\n",
    "    yhat = invert_scale(transform, x_test, yhat)\n",
    "    yhat = inverse_difference(AU_influenza, yhat, len(x_test)+1-i)\n",
    "    predictions.append(yhat)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 104,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "[<matplotlib.lines.Line2D at 0x1c41afeef0>]"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 104,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    },
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1440x576 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "plt.figure(figsize=(20,8))\n",
    "predictions = pd.Series(predictions)\n",
    "predictions.index = AU_influenza[split:-1].index\n",
    "plt.plot(AU_influenza[split:])\n",
    "plt.plot(predictions)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 105,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "1880.6311599984763"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 105,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "sqrt(mean_squared_error(AU_influenza[split:-1], predictions))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Getting 6 months predictions"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 126,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "#transform full dataset\n",
    "\n",
    "x_ = transform.transform(x)\n",
    "y_ = transform.transform(y)    \n",
    "    \n",
    "x_ = x_.reshape(x_.shape[0], 1, x_.shape[1])\n",
    "\n",
    "model = Sequential()\n",
    "model.add(LSTM(5, batch_input_shape=(1, x_.shape[1], x_.shape[2]), stateful=True))\n",
    "model.add(Dense(1))\n",
    "model.compile(loss='mean_squared_error', optimizer='adam')\n",
    "for i in range(2000):\n",
    "    model.fit(x_, y_, epochs=1, batch_size=1, verbose=0, shuffle=False)\n",
    "    model.reset_states()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 127,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "%%capture\n",
    "x_r = x_.reshape(len(x_), 1, 1)\n",
    "p = list(model.predict(train_reshaped, batch_size=1))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 129,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "lstm_predictons = []\n",
    "for i in range(7):\n",
    "    x_in = p[-1].reshape(1, 1, 1)\n",
    "    yhat = model.predict(x_in, batch_size=1)\n",
    "    p.append(yhat)\n",
    "    yhat = invert_scale(transform, x_, yhat)\n",
    "    yhat = inverse_difference(AU_influenza, yhat, len(x_)+1-i)\n",
    "    lstm_predictons.append(yhat)\n",
    "pd.DataFrame(lstm_predictons).to_csv('lstm_predictions.csv')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [

    "\n",
    "From here we can see the real test: short term vs long term models for this particular problem. "
